00:19:35,171 --> 00:19:39,471
I'd have to go up to the wives
in the library or the supermarket...

257
00:19:39,771 --> 00:19:42,271
...and say, "Hello, I am new here."

258
00:19:42,671 --> 00:19:46,071
"You must be Mrs. So-and-so,
Doctor So-and-so's wife."

259
00:19:46,271 --> 00:19:48,571
It really wasn't very nice at all.

260
00:19:52,471 --> 00:19:53,971
Daddy knows how to run things.

261
00:19:54,771 --> 00:19:56,171
He's a remarkable man.

262
00:19:56,471 --> 00:19:57,771
You bet your sweet life.

263
00:19:58,771 --> 00:19:59,971
I'll tell you a secret.

264
00:20:00,671 --> 00:20:05,171
There are easier things in this world,
if you teach at the university...

265
00:20:05,471 --> 00:20:07,471
...than being married
to the daughter of...

266
00:20:07,871 --> 00:20:11,471
...the president of that university.
There are easier things.

267
00:20:11,871 --> 00:20:16,771
It's a great opportunity. For some men
it would be the chance of a lifetime.

268
00:20:16,971 --> 00:20:20,471
There are, believe me,
easier things in this world.

269
00:20:20,871 --> 00:20:23,471
Some men would give their right arm
for the chance!

270
00:20:23,871 --> 00:20:28,371
In reality that sacrifice is of a more
private portion of the anatomy.

271
00:20:30,671 --> 00:20:32,371
Could you show me where the...

272
00:20:32,871 --> 00:20:33,671
Are you all right?

273
00:20:34,071 --> 00:20:38,171
Of course, dear. I just want to
put some powder on my nose.

274
00:20:38,671 --> 00:20:40,871
Show her where we keep the euphemism?

275
00:20:45,071 --> 00:20:47,871
I'm sorry. I want to show you
the house anyway.

276
00:20:48,571 --> 00:20:50,071
We'll be back, dear.

277
00:20:51,171 --> 00:20:53,571
Honestly, George, you burn me up!

278
00:20:54,171 --> 00:20:55,171
You really do!

279
00:20:57,171 --> 00:20:59,571
Don't shoot your mouth off
about you-know-what.

280
00:21:00,171 --> 00:21:03,171
I'll talk about
any goddamn thing I want to!

281
00:21:03,571 --> 00:21:04,671
Okay, vanish!

282
00:21:05,071 --> 00:21:07,371
Any goddamn thing I want!

283
00:21:37,571 --> 00:21:38,871
What'll it be?

284
00:21:39,071 --> 00:21:40,571
I'll stick to bourbon.

285
00:21:48,071 --> 00:21:50,271
You're in the Math Department?

286
00:21:50,471 --> 00:21:51,371
No.

287
00:21:55,771 --> 00:21:58,071
Martha said so.
I think that's what she said.

288
00:22:05,071 --> 00:22:06,771
Why'd you decide to be a teacher?

289
00:22:08,471 --> 00:22:11,071
The same things that motivated you,
I imagine.

290
00:22:11,471 --> 00:22:12,771
Oh? What were they?

291
00:22:13,971 --> 00:22:15,971
What were the things that motivated me?

292
00:22:16,771 --> 00:22:18,271
Well, I'm sure I don't know.

293
00:22:18,471 --> 00:22:21,271
You said the things that motivated you
and me were the same.

294
00:22:21,671 --> 00:22:22,971
I said I imagined they were.

295
00:22:23,471 --> 00:22:24,571
Oh, did you?

296
00:22:35,971 --> 00:22:37,271
You like it here?

297
00:22:39,271 --> 00:22:40,471
Yes, it's fine.

298
00:22:40,771 --> 00:22:42,171
I meant the university.

299
00:22:43,871 --> 00:22:46,071
I know. I meant the university.

300
00:22:47,171 --> 00:22:48,971
Well, I like it fine.

301
00:23:02,371 --> 00:23:05,971
You've been here for quite a long time,
haven't you?

302
00:23:10,971 --> 00:23:15,171
Oh, yes. Ever since I married
what's-her-name. Martha.

303
00:23:16,371 --> 00:23:18,871
Even before that. Forever.

304
00:23:19,371 --> 00:23:21,171
Dashed hopes and good intentions.

305
00:23:22,171 --> 00:23:25,171
Good, better, best, bested!

306
00:23:27,371 --> 00:23:29,171
How do you like that for a declension?

307
00:23:29,671 --> 00:23:31,071
You didn't answer my question.

308
00:23:32,071 --> 00:23:36,571
Don't condescend. I asked you
how you liked that declension.

309
00:23:38,671 --> 00:23:40,071
I don't know what to say.

310
00:23:40,571 --> 00:23:41,871
You don't know what to say?

311
00:23:42,471 --> 00:23:45,871
Shall I say it's funny,
so you can say it's sad?

312
00:23:46,071 --> 00:23:50,871
Or shall I say it's sad so you can say
it's funny? You can play that game!

313
00:23:51,471 --> 00:23:53,371
- Very good!
- I think we'll just...

314
00:23:53,871 --> 00:23:56,371
Now, calm down. Just calm down.
All right?

315
00:23:56,771 --> 00:23:57,871
Another drink? Here.

316
00:23:58,271 --> 00:24:00,571
I still have one.
And when my wife comes down...

317
00:24:02,271 --> 00:24:06,871
What I mean is, you and your wife
seem to be having some sort of a...

318
00:24:07,571 --> 00:24:11,271
Martha and I are having nothing.
Martha and I are merely exercising.

319
00:24:11,571 --> 00:24:14,771
We're walking what's left of our wits.
Pay no attention.

320
00:24:15,071 --> 00:24:17,071
Now let's sit down and talk, huh?

321
00:24:17,771 --> 00:24:21,571
It's just I don't like to become
involved in other people's affairs.

322
00:24:22,071 --> 00:24:25,771
You'll get over that. Small college.
Musical beds is the faculty sport.

323
00:24:26,071 --> 00:24:26,971
Sir?

324
00:24:27,271 --> 00:24:30,071
Never mind. I wish you wouldn't go
"sir." How old are you?

325
00:24:30,571 --> 00:24:31,571
Twenty-eight.

326
00:24:31,771 --> 00:24:33,071
I'm forty-something.

327
00:24:34,171 --> 00:24:36,571
Aren't you surprised?
Don't I look older?

328
00:24:39,071 --> 00:24:40,471
I think you look fine.

329
00:24:40,771 --> 00:24:44,071
I've always been lean. I play handball.
How much do you weigh?

330
00:24:45,571 --> 00:24:48,471
155,160, something like that?
You play handball?

331
00:24:48,771 --> 00:24:50,671
- Not very well.
- We'll play sometime.

332
00:24:50,871 --> 00:24:55,271
Martha is 108... years old.
She weighs somewhat more than that.

333
00:24:55,571 --> 00:24:56,571
How old is your wife?

334
00:24:57,971 --> 00:24:59,271
She's twenty-six.

335
00:24:59,671 --> 00:25:03,171
Martha is a remarkable woman.
I imagine she weighs around 110.

336
00:25:03,471 --> 00:25:04,471
Your wife weighs...

337
00:25:04,771 --> 00:25:07,271
No, my boy, your wife.
My wife is Martha.

338
00:25:07,971 --> 00:25:09,271
Yes, I know.

339
00:25:09,771 --> 00:25:12,971
If you were married to Martha
you'd know what it means.

340
00:25:14,471 --> 00:25:16,971
If I were married to your wife,
I'd know what that means.

341
00:25:21,171 --> 00:25:24,271
Martha says you are in
the Math Department or something.

342
00:25:25,771 --> 00:25:26,771
No, I'm not.

343
00:25:27,171 --> 00:25:30,271
She's seldom mistaken.
Maybe you should be in it.

344
00:25:31,171 --> 00:25:33,771
I'm a biologist.
I'm in the Biology Department.

345
00:25:38,671 --> 00:25:42,971
You're the one's going to make all
that trouble making everyone the same.

346
00:25:43,371 --> 00:25:46,471
Rearranging the chromozones,
or whatever it is, right?

347
00:25:47,671 --> 00:25:49,471
Not exactly. Chromosomes.

348
00:25:49,971 --> 00:25:51,171
I'm very mistrustful.

349
00:25:52,471 --> 00:25:55,971
You think we learn nothing from history?
I'm in the History Department.

350
00:25:56,771 --> 00:25:57,671
Yes, I know.

351
00:25:57,871 --> 00:26:00,371
Martha tells me I'm in
the History Department...

352
00:26:00,671 --> 00:26:05,171
...as opposed to being the History
Department, in the sense of running it.

353
00:26:05,471 --> 00:26:08,371
I do not run the History Department.

354
00:26:08,671 --> 00:26:10,571
I don't run the Biology Department.

355
00:26:10,771 --> 00:26:12,371
You're twenty-one. Twenty-eight.

356
00:26:12,871 --> 00:26:16,871
Perhaps when you're forty-something
you'll run the History Department.

357
00:26:17,671 --> 00:26:19,071
Biology Department.

358
00:26:19,571 --> 00:26:22,071
I'm really very mistrustful!

359
00:26:22,871 --> 00:26:26,871
I read somewhere that science fiction
is not really fiction at all.

360
00:26:27,171 --> 00:26:31,371
That you rearrange my genes so that
everyone will be like everyone else.

361
00:26:31,671 --> 00:26:34,571
I suspect we shall not have
much music or painting.

362
00:26:35,271 --> 00:26:39,571
But we'll have a civilization of
sublime young men much like yourself.

363
00:26:39,871 --> 00:26:44,071
Cultures and races will vanish.
The ants will take over the world.

364
00:26:44,771 --> 00:26:46,571
Don't know much about science, do you?

365
00:26:46,871 --> 00:26:49,771
I know history.
I know when I'm being threatened.

366
00:26:51,871 --> 00:26:54,071
Your wife doesn't have any hips,
does she?

367
00:26:56,071 --> 00:27:00,371
I'm not hip-happy. I was implying
that your wife is slim-hipped.

368
00:27:01,771 --> 00:27:02,971
Yes, she is.

369
00:27:03,571 --> 00:27:04,571
You got any kids?

370
00:27:05,271 --> 00:27:07,071
No. Not yet. You?

371
00:27:07,371 --> 00:27:08,871
For me to know and you to find out.

372
00:27:12,271 --> 00:27:13,671
No kids, huh?

373
00:27:14,571 --> 00:27:15,371
What's wrong?

374
00:27:16,071 --> 00:27:18,871
Nothing. We wanted to wait
till we're settled.

375
00:27:22,471 --> 00:27:24,071
Think you'll be happy
here at New Carthage?

376
00:27:24,771 --> 00:27:28,071
Well, we hope to stay here.
I don't mean forever.

377
00:27:28,571 --> 00:27:31,771
Don't bandy that about.
The Old Man wouldn't like it.

378
00:27:33,471 --> 00:27:37,571
Martha's father expects his staff
to come here and grow old...

379
00:27:37,971 --> 00:27:40,371
...and fall in the line of service.

380
00:27:40,571 --> 00:27:42,771
One man, a professor of Latin...

381
00:27:43,071 --> 00:27:45,771
...actually fell in the
cafeteria line one lunch.

382
00:27:46,071 --> 00:27:49,671
But the Old Man isn't falling anywhere.
He isn't going to die.

383
00:27:50,471 --> 00:27:51,771
There are rumors...

384
00:27:52,171 --> 00:27:55,771
...which you can't breathe to Martha
for she foams at the mouth...

385
00:27:56,271 --> 00:27:57,771
...that the Old Man, her father...

386
00:27:58,171 --> 00:28:01,271
...is over two hundred years old.

387
00:28:01,771 --> 00:28:04,971
There's an irony there, but I'm not
drunk enough to figure it out.

388
00:28:08,671 --> 00:28:09,671
Damnit!

389
00:28:10,271 --> 00:28:13,671
I wonder what women talk about
when men talk. I must find out.

390
00:28:14,271 --> 00:28:15,971
What do you want?

391
00:28:18,271 --> 00:28:20,171
Isn't that a wonderful sound?

392
00:28:20,971 --> 00:28:22,371
How many kids you having?

393
00:28:23,371 --> 00:28:24,971
I don't know. My wife is...

394
00:28:25,371 --> 00:28:28,171
Slim-hipped.
Well, there's one of you at least.

395
00:28:28,471 --> 00:28:33,171
You must see this house, dear.
This is such a wonderful old house.

396
00:28:34,671 --> 00:28:36,971
For Christ's sake, hang on a minute!

397
00:28:37,171 --> 00:28:38,971
She'll be right down, she's changing.

398
00:28:39,371 --> 00:28:41,371
She's changing? What, her clothes?

399
00:28:41,571 --> 00:28:42,971
- Her dress.
- Why?

400
00:28:43,171 --> 00:28:45,971
I imagine that she wants
to be comfortable.

401
00:28:46,171 --> 00:28:47,871
Oh, she does, does she?

402
00:28:48,171 --> 00:28:49,671
You don't know!

403
00:28:51,771 --> 00:28:54,671
- You all right, dear?
- Yes, dear, perfectly fine.

404
00:28:55,371 --> 00:28:56,871
She wants to be comfortable?

405
00:28:57,571 --> 00:28:58,871
Well, we'll see about that!

406
00:28:59,371 --> 00:29:01,171
I didn't know that you had a son.

407
00:29:04,371 --> 00:29:07,371
- A son. I hadn't known.
- You to know and me to find out, huh?

408
00:29:07,671 --> 00:29:10,371
Tomorrow is his birthday.
He will be sixteen.

409
00:29:11,971 --> 00:29:12,871
She told you?

410
00:29:13,971 --> 00:29:15,671
- She told you about him?
- Yes.

411
00:29:16,871 --> 00:29:18,471
You said she's changing?

412
00:29:19,471 --> 00:29:21,371
- And she mentioned...
- Your son's birthday.

413
00:29:26,171 --> 00:29:27,771
You look pale. Would you like...

414
00:29:28,071 --> 00:29:31,571
Yes, dear a little more brandy maybe.
Just a drop.

415
00:29:32,471 --> 00:29:33,571
The bar?

416
00:29:34,071 --> 00:29:37,871
Yes, by all means, drink away.
You'll need it as years go on.

417
00:29:39,371 --> 00:29:41,271
Damn destructive...

418
00:29:41,571 --> 00:29:43,071
What time is it, dear?

419
00:29:44,471 --> 00:29:46,571
- 2:30.
- So late!

420
00:29:46,871 --> 00:29:48,071
We should get home.

421
00:29:48,571 --> 00:29:50,071
Keeping the baby sitter up?

422
00:29:51,871 --> 00:29:53,371
I said we didn't have children.

423
00:29:54,271 --> 00:29:56,271
Sorry, I wasn't even listening.

424
00:29:56,571 --> 00:29:58,371
Or thinking. Whichever applies.

425
00:29:59,271 --> 00:30:00,371
We'll go in a while.

426
00:30:00,771 --> 00:30:02,271
No, you mustn't!

427
00:30:02,671 --> 00:30:07,771
Martha is changing, and not for me.
Martha hasn't changed for me in years.

428
00:30:08,071 --> 00:30:12,071
It means we're going to be here days.
You're being accorded an honor.

429
00:30:12,471 --> 00:30:16,571
Don't forget Martha is the daughter
of our beloved boss... his right arm.

430
00:30:17,271 --> 00:30:19,971
I'd use another word,
but leave that sort of talk to Martha.

431
00:30:20,471 --> 00:30:21,771
What sort of talk?

432
00:30:25,971 --> 00:30:26,971
Well, now!

433
00:30:29,271 --> 00:30:31,371
Why, Martha, your Sunday chapel dress!

434
00:30:31,771 --> 00:30:34,071
Oh, that's most attractive!

435
00:30:34,471 --> 00:30:35,771
You like it? Good.

436
00:30:37,171 --> 00:30:39,771
What do you mean screaming
up the stairs at me?

437
00:30:39,971 --> 00:30:43,071
We got lonely for the soft purr
of your little voice.

438
00:30:43,771 --> 00:30:46,571
Well, you just trot over
to the bar-ie-poo...

439
00:30:46,971 --> 00:30:49,971
...and make your little mommy
a gweat big dwink.

440
00:30:50,271 --> 00:30:51,471
That's right!

441
00:30:54,871 --> 00:30:59,271
You're quite a guy, getting your masters
when you were what, 12?

442
00:31:00,171 --> 00:31:02,571
- Hear that, George?
- 12 and a half, actually.

443
00:31:03,471 --> 00:31:04,471
19, really.

444
00:31:04,671 --> 00:31:07,571
- You needn't have mentioned it.
- I'm proud of you!

445
00:31:07,771 --> 00:31:10,071
- I'm very impressed.
- You're damn right!

446
00:31:10,271 --> 00:31:14,171
I'm wracked with jealousy.
What do you want me to do, throw up?

447
00:31:15,471 --> 00:31:18,171
That's very impressive.
You should be proud.

448
00:31:18,471 --> 00:31:20,471
He's a pretty nice fellow.

449
00:31:21,171 --> 00:31:23,271
You might take over
the History Department.

450
00:31:23,471 --> 00:31:24,771
Biology Department.

451
00:31:25,471 --> 00:31:27,171
Yes. I'm preoccupied with history.

452
00:31:29,171 --> 00:31:31,971
What a remark.
"I am preoccupied with history."

453
00:31:34,471 --> 00:31:38,471
George is not. George is preoccupied
with the History Department.

454
00:31:38,971 --> 00:31:40,971
He's preoccupied with it...

455
00:31:41,371 --> 00:31:45,471
...because he is not the
History Department, he is only in it.

456
00:31:45,871 --> 00:31:48,371
We went through that
while you were upstairs.

457
00:31:48,671 --> 00:31:50,471
That's right, baby, keep it clean.

458
00:31:51,371 --> 00:31:54,171
George is bogged down
in the History Department.

459
00:31:55,371 --> 00:31:57,871
He's an old bog
in the History Department.

460
00:31:58,371 --> 00:31:59,871
That's what George is...

461
00:32:00,071 --> 00:32:04,071
...A bog, a fen, a G.D. Swamp!

462
00:32:07,571 --> 00:32:09,971
Hey, swamp! Hey, swampy!

463
00:32:15,071 --> 00:32:16,171
Can I get you something?

464
00:32:18,371 --> 00:32:19,171
Well, sure.

465
00:32:19,671 --> 00:32:23,371
You can light my cigarette
if you're of a mind to.

466
00:32:23,771 --> 00:32:25,671
No. There are limits.

467
00:32:26,571 --> 00:32:28,071
A man puts up with only so much...

468
00:32:28,371 --> 00:32:32,071
...before he descends on the
evolutionary ladder which is your line.

469
00:32:32,871 --> 00:32:36,671
I'll hold your hand when it's dark
and you're afraid of the bogeyman.

470
00:32:37,071 --> 00:32:40,071
And I'll tote your gin bottles
out after midnight so no one sees.

471
00:32:40,371 --> 00:32:44,671
But I will not light your cigarette.
And that, as they say, is that.

472
00:32:50,871 --> 00:32:53,071
Hey, you played football, huh?

473
00:32:53,471 --> 00:32:55,271
Yes, I was a quarterback.

474
00:32:55,471 --> 00:32:57,871
But I was much more adept at boxing.

475
00:32:58,771 --> 00:33:01,371
Boxing? You hear that, George?

476
00:33:02,971 --> 00:33:06,071
Must've been good. Doesn't look
like you got hit in the face.

477
00:33:06,471 --> 00:33:09,271
He was intercollegiate state
middleweight champion.

478
00:33:11,071 --> 00:33:14,271
Still looks like you have a
pretty good body, is that right?

479
00:33:14,471 --> 00:33:15,871
Decency forbids...

480
00:33:16,071 --> 00:33:17,271
Shut up!

481
00:33:17,771 --> 00:33:20,771
Is that right?
Have you kept your body up?

482
00:33:21,271 --> 00:33:23,771
It's still pretty good. I work out.

483
00:33:25,471 --> 00:33:28,071
Yes, he has a very firm body.

484
00:33:28,671 --> 00:33:31,071
Have you? I think that's very nice.

485
00:33:31,471 --> 00:33:34,071
You know, once you have it,
you never know...

486
00:33:34,471 --> 00:33:35,971
...when it'll come in handy!

487
00:33:38,671 --> 00:33:41,071
I say, why give it up until you have to?

488
00:33:44,871 --> 00:33:47,071
I couldn't agree with you more!

489
00:33:47,471 --> 00:33:49,071
Your obscenity is beyond human...

490
00:33:49,471 --> 00:33:52,271
George here doesn't cotton
too much to body talk.

491
00:33:52,571 --> 00:33:57,471
Paunchy isn't happy when the talk
moves to muscles. How much you weigh?

492
00:33:59,371 --> 00:34:00,771
155,150...

493
00:34:01,971 --> 00:34:04,971
Still at the old middleweight limit?
That's pretty good!

494
00:34:08,871 --> 00:34:11,171
Tell them about the boxing match we had.

495
00:34:12,971 --> 00:34:13,771
Christ!

496
00:34:15,471 --> 00:34:16,771
Tell them about it.

497
00:34:17,071 --> 00:34:19,171
You tell them, you're good at it.

498
00:34:19,571 --> 00:34:22,271
- Is he all right?
- Him? Oh, sure.

499
00:34:23,371 --> 00:34:25,071
We had this boxing match...

500
00:34:25,371 --> 00:34:27,271
