01:56:40,871 --> 01:56:43,471
Through one failure after another.

1726
01:56:43,871 --> 01:56:47,671
Each attempt more numbing,
more sickening than the one before.

1727
01:56:48,571 --> 01:56:51,871
The one thing, the one person
I tried to protect...

1728
01:56:52,571 --> 01:56:56,971
...to raise above the mire of this vile,
crushing marriage...

1729
01:56:57,871 --> 01:57:01,871
...the one light in all this
hopeless darkness! Our son!

1730
01:57:02,071 --> 01:57:02,871
Stop it!

1731
01:57:07,471 --> 01:57:08,971
Why, don't you like it?

1732
01:57:09,371 --> 01:57:10,671
You can't do this.

1733
01:57:10,871 --> 01:57:11,671
Who says?

1734
01:57:11,671 --> 01:57:14,071
- I say!
- Tell us why, baby.

1735
01:57:15,071 --> 01:57:16,471
Is this game over?

1736
01:57:19,071 --> 01:57:20,971
Oh, no! Not by a long shot.

1737
01:57:22,071 --> 01:57:24,871
I've got a surprise for you.
It's about sonny-Jim.

1738
01:57:26,871 --> 01:57:28,371
I'm running this show!

1739
01:57:29,371 --> 01:57:30,371
Sweetheart...

1740
01:57:31,071 --> 01:57:33,871
...I'm afraid I've got
some bad news for you.

1741
01:57:34,071 --> 01:57:36,371
For both of us, I mean.
Some rather sad news.

1742
01:57:37,371 --> 01:57:38,871
What is this?

1743
01:57:39,071 --> 01:57:43,071
Martha, while you were busy,
while the two of you were busy...

1744
01:57:43,371 --> 01:57:45,371
...I don't know where,
but you were somewhere...

1745
01:57:45,871 --> 01:57:47,771
...while you were busy for awhile...

1746
01:57:48,571 --> 01:57:51,271
...Missy and I
were having a little talk.

1747
01:57:51,471 --> 01:57:53,571
You know, a chaw and a talk.

1748
01:57:53,771 --> 01:57:55,471
And the doorbell rang.

1749
01:57:55,671 --> 01:57:56,671
Chimed.

1750
01:58:03,271 --> 01:58:04,571
It's hard for me to tell you.

1751
01:58:06,271 --> 01:58:07,471
Please don't!

1752
01:58:07,771 --> 01:58:08,771
Tell me!

1753
01:58:09,771 --> 01:58:13,771
It was good old Western Union,
some little boy about seventy.

1754
01:58:14,771 --> 01:58:15,671
Crazy Billy?

1755
01:58:16,071 --> 01:58:17,571
That's right. Crazy Billy.

1756
01:58:18,271 --> 01:58:20,771
And he had a telegram and it was for us.

1757
01:58:22,771 --> 01:58:23,871
I have to tell you about it.

1758
01:58:25,471 --> 01:58:29,771
Why did they bring it?
Why didn't they telephone it?

1759
01:58:30,271 --> 01:58:34,871
There are some telegrams you have to
deliver, Martha. Some you cannot phone.

1760
01:58:36,271 --> 01:58:37,571
What do you mean?

1761
01:58:40,271 --> 01:58:41,971
I can hardly bring myself to say it.

1762
01:58:42,971 --> 01:58:44,071
You want to do it?

1763
01:58:49,771 --> 01:58:54,271
Well, Martha, I'm afraid our boy
isn't coming home for his birthday.

1764
01:58:55,171 --> 01:58:56,571
Of course he is!

1765
01:58:57,471 --> 01:58:59,071
Of course he is! I say he is!

1766
01:58:59,471 --> 01:59:00,271
He can't.

1767
01:59:04,671 --> 01:59:05,871
Our son...

1768
01:59:06,971 --> 01:59:07,971
...is...

1769
01:59:09,571 --> 01:59:10,371
...dead.

1770
01:59:11,971 --> 01:59:14,671
He was killed late in the afternoon...

1771
01:59:15,371 --> 01:59:17,571
...on a country road with his
learner's permit.

1772
01:59:17,771 --> 01:59:20,271
He swerved to avoid a porcupine
and drove...

1773
01:59:20,671 --> 01:59:21,771
You can't do that!

1774
01:59:22,871 --> 01:59:24,171
...into a large tree.

1775
01:59:25,271 --> 01:59:26,771
You cannot do that!

1776
01:59:28,471 --> 01:59:29,971
I thought you should know.

1777
01:59:31,771 --> 01:59:33,471
You cannot do that!

1778
01:59:33,771 --> 01:59:36,671
You can't decide these things
for yourself!

1779
01:59:37,271 --> 01:59:39,171
I will not let you do that!

1780
01:59:39,471 --> 01:59:41,171
Have to leave around noon, I suppose.

1781
01:59:41,471 --> 01:59:43,471
I won't let you decide these things.

1782
01:59:43,671 --> 01:59:46,971
There are matters of identification,
arrangements to be made.

1783
01:59:47,371 --> 01:59:49,471
You can't do this! I won't let you!

1784
01:59:50,171 --> 01:59:52,971
- Get your hands off me!
- I haven't done anything!

1785
01:59:53,371 --> 01:59:55,671
Now you listen to me. Our son is dead!

1786
01:59:55,871 --> 01:59:57,471
Can you get that through your head?

1787
01:59:58,471 --> 02:00:02,871
Listen carefully. We got a telegram.
There was a car accident and he's dead!

1788
02:00:03,171 --> 02:00:05,871
Poof! Just like that!
Now how do you like it?

1789
02:00:09,971 --> 02:00:11,971
Let her go.
She'll be all right.

1790
02:00:23,171 --> 02:00:25,571
He is not dead.

1791
02:00:28,071 --> 02:00:29,071
He is dead.

1792
02:00:34,371 --> 02:00:36,671
You cannot decide.

1793
02:00:37,671 --> 02:00:39,171
He hasn't decided anything.

1794
02:00:39,571 --> 02:00:42,671
It's not his doing.
He doesn't have the power.

1795
02:00:43,071 --> 02:00:47,371
That's right. I'm no god. I have
no power over life and death, do I?

1796
02:00:49,271 --> 02:00:51,371
You can't kill him.

1797
02:00:51,771 --> 02:00:54,271
You can't let him die!

1798
02:00:59,171 --> 02:01:00,571
There was a telegram.

1799
02:01:04,271 --> 02:01:07,571
Show it to me! Show me that telegram!

1800
02:01:12,571 --> 02:01:13,571
I ate it.

1801
02:01:14,871 --> 02:01:17,071
What did you just say to me?

1802
02:01:18,171 --> 02:01:20,771
I ate it.

1803
02:01:24,071 --> 02:01:25,471
Good for you, Martha.

1804
02:01:26,071 --> 02:01:28,971
You make a joke at a time like this?

1805
02:01:29,171 --> 02:01:30,571
Did I not eat the telegram?

1806
02:01:30,771 --> 02:01:33,571
You ate it. I watched you
and you ate it all down.

1807
02:01:33,971 --> 02:01:34,971
Like a good boy.

1808
02:01:36,471 --> 02:01:38,371
You won't get away with this.

1809
02:01:40,571 --> 02:01:42,971
You know the rules, for God's sake!

1810
02:01:44,271 --> 02:01:45,771
What are you talking about?

1811
02:01:46,071 --> 02:01:47,471
I can kill him if I want to.

1812
02:01:47,771 --> 02:01:48,871
He is our child.

1813
02:01:49,071 --> 02:01:52,371
- You bore him. A good delivery.
- He is our child.

1814
02:01:52,571 --> 02:01:53,771
And I've killed him.

1815
02:01:56,171 --> 02:01:58,671
Oh my God, I think I understand this.

1816
02:01:59,171 --> 02:02:00,071
Do you?

1817
02:02:00,871 --> 02:02:04,171
- Oh my God, I think I understand this.
- Good for you.

1818
02:02:08,871 --> 02:02:12,071
You've no right.
You've no right at all.

1819
02:02:12,271 --> 02:02:16,771
I have the right, we never spoke of it.
I could kill him any time I wanted.

1820
02:02:16,971 --> 02:02:18,671
Why?

1821
02:02:18,971 --> 02:02:20,171
You broke our rule, Martha.

1822
02:02:20,471 --> 02:02:23,971
You mentioned him to somebody else.

1823
02:02:24,271 --> 02:02:26,171
- I did not.
- Yes, you did.

1824
02:02:29,671 --> 02:02:31,671
To me, you mentioned him to me.

1825
02:02:34,871 --> 02:02:35,971
I forget.

1826
02:02:37,371 --> 02:02:41,271
Sometimes when it's late night
and everybody's talking...

1827
02:02:41,671 --> 02:02:43,671
...I forget and I want to mention him.

1828
02:02:43,971 --> 02:02:46,671
But I hold on. I hold on.

1829
02:02:48,071 --> 02:02:50,671
I've wanted to so often.

1830
02:02:51,671 --> 02:02:53,671
But, George, you've pushed it.

1831
02:02:53,971 --> 02:02:57,171
There was no need,
there was no need for this!

1832
02:02:58,871 --> 02:03:00,671
I mentioned him, all right?

1833
02:03:01,971 --> 02:03:04,571
But you didn't have
to push it over the edge.

1834
02:03:05,371 --> 02:03:07,371
You didn't have to kill him.

1835
02:03:15,371 --> 02:03:18,871
You didn't have to have him die.

1836
02:03:24,571 --> 02:03:27,171
That wasn't needed.

1837
02:03:56,871 --> 02:03:58,371
It's dawn.

1838
02:03:59,971 --> 02:04:01,871
I think the party's over.

1839
02:04:07,771 --> 02:04:09,471
You couldn't have any?

1840
02:04:12,171 --> 02:04:13,371
We couldn't.

1841
02:04:18,271 --> 02:04:21,071
Home to bed, children.
It's way past your bedtime.

1842
02:04:32,071 --> 02:04:33,471
You two go now.

1843
02:04:47,771 --> 02:04:49,671
- I'd like to...
- Goodnight.

1844
02:05:16,771 --> 02:05:18,171
You want anything?

1845
02:05:19,471 --> 02:05:20,971
No. Nothing.

1846
02:05:26,771 --> 02:05:28,171
Time for bed.

1847
02:05:34,871 --> 02:05:35,871
Tired?

1848
02:05:36,271 --> 02:05:37,271
Yes.

1849
02:05:38,571 --> 02:05:39,571
I am.

1850
02:05:48,971 --> 02:05:50,571
Sunday tomorrow.

1851
02:05:52,971 --> 02:05:54,171
All day.

1852
02:06:31,771 --> 02:06:33,771
Did you have to?

1853
02:06:35,871 --> 02:06:36,871
Yes.

1854
02:06:41,771 --> 02:06:43,071
You had to?

1855
02:06:49,771 --> 02:06:50,871
I don't know.

1856
02:06:54,371 --> 02:06:56,571
- It was time.
- Was it?

1857
02:07:07,971 --> 02:07:09,371
I'm cold.

1858
02:07:11,971 --> 02:07:12,971
It's late.

1859
02:07:25,571 --> 02:07:26,971
It will be better.

1860
02:07:30,371 --> 02:07:31,871
I don't know.

1861
02:07:32,971 --> 02:07:34,671
It will be. Maybe.

1862
02:07:37,171 --> 02:07:38,971
I'm not sure.

1863
02:07:47,771 --> 02:07:48,971
Just us?

1864
02:07:53,471 --> 02:07:55,171
- You don't suppose maybe...
- No.

1865
02:08:09,171 --> 02:08:10,871
- You all right?
- Yes.

1866
02:08:16,671 --> 02:08:17,671
No.

1867
02:08:22,871 --> 02:08:26,271
Who's afraid of Virginia Woolf?

1868
02:08:28,671 --> 02:08:29,971
I am, George.

1869
02:08:33,671 --> 02:08:34,971
I am, George.

1870
02:08:36,971 --> 02:08:38,071
I am.

